The tradeoff between off & on-the-grid setups is that the 1st is more selfish, benefitting mainly the #bitcoin blockchain, especially when stranded sources are fossil, while the 2nd is more generous as it benefits both the #bitcoin blockchain & nature‚Äôs organic blockchain. 19/19

There is no counter indication to this net-positive strategy in terms of #bitcoin resiliency. If we choose the lesser-negative-but-still-net-negative strategy, it‚Äôs purely for financial, Cantillon-based, seigniorage induced, #bitcoin-independent greedy motives. 18/19

As soon as #bitcoin mining has produced enough to pay for wells‚Äô closures, land remediation & a margin for miners, it's more effective overall to close stranded wells, remediate lands & move those mining rigs to other stranded wells for a new round of closures. 17/19

The all-round net-positive solution would be using #bitcoin mining with stranded gas to pay for the closure of the same wells powering the mining & the environmental remediation of lands polluted by those wells, while still contributing to the #bitcoin network. 16/19

From a #bitcoin perspective, it seems paradoxical & contradictory that mining, with its philosophical foundations steeped in sound money principles, should piggyback on the shoulders of those very same central banks that flooded the oil & gas space with easy money. 15/19

@nic__carter & @danheld among others have underlined the advantages of using stranded, ‚Äúnon-rival‚Äù energy sources to mine #bitcoin. Personally, I see net economic/climate/environmental/philosophical benefits only using renewable stranded sources, like hydro. 12/19

Moving mining rigs & people to remote locations to exploit stranded resources might well still make sense decades from now, but #bitcoin should probably envision a situation where a very sizable portion of mining is done on the grid near traditional locations. 11/19

Often, stranded resources have remained so even if they are cheap because they are cut off in too many ways from other networks. #bitcoin mining might not be enough to cover non-energy costs associated with remote locations & connect all the dots, even in a digital era. 10/19

On the other hand, I‚Äôm somewhat skeptical about the idea that the availability of cheap, stranded energy in a remote location on its own will be enough to spark the development of whole communities around #bitcoin mining. 7/19

The incentives for this rebalancing of roles between off & on-the-grid setups seem potent: decarbonization & energy-independence goals broadly push electrification & renewables, which drive grid investments, which favour on-the-grid #bitcoin mining. 6/19

The two setups can cover different types of off-&-on-the-grid locations, but they tend to be alternative to each other. To the extent the narrative & reality of #bitcoin mining as a power flexibility provider expands, its bottom-feeder role could become more marginal. 4/19

The appeal of this narrative about #bitcoin as the ideal solution to monetize & financially store stranded energy sources is somewhat shrinking as the prospects of using #bitcoin mining as the ideal provider of grid flexibility services grow. 3/19 @nlw

How does off-the-grid #bitcoin mining in remote locations with stranded energy fit with #bitcoin mining as an on-the-grid provider of power demand-response & flexibility services? The short answer is: with clear tradeoffs. 1/19 @Crypto_Mags @thetrocro @jyn_urso @progressivebtcr
